  <!-- ─── STEP 3: Build Make.com Scenario ─── -->
  <div class="step-card">
    <div class="time-badge">⏱ 45 min</div>
    <div class="step-card-header">
      <div class="step-num-big">3</div>
      <div>
        <div class="step-card-title">Build the Make.com Automation Scenario</div>
        <div class="step-card-sub">Your central router — this is where all the tools connect together</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="step-body">
      <p>In Make.com, go to <strong>Scenarios → Create a new Scenario</strong>. You will build a chain of modules that process every incoming WhatsApp message. Here is the exact module order:</p>

      <div class="scenario-map">
        <div class="sm-row">
          <div class="sm-num">M1</div>
          <div class="sm-content">
            <div class="sm-title"><span class="sm-tag">Trigger</span> Webhooks → Custom Webhook</div>
            <div class="sm-desc">Click "Add" → name it "WhatsApp Incoming" → copy the generated URL → paste it into your Meta Webhooks panel from Step 2. This module fires every time a message arrives.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="sm-row">
          <div class="sm-num">M2</div>
          <div class="sm-content">
            <div class="sm-title"><span class="sm-tag">Action</span> HTTP → Make a Request (OpenAI)</div>
            <div class="sm-desc">POST to https://api.openai.com/v1/chat/completions. Pass the incoming message body from M1 as the user message. Add your OpenAI API key in the Authorization header as "Bearer sk-...". Set model to "gpt-4o-mini" for cost efficiency.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="sm-row">
          <div class="sm-num">M3</div>
          <div class="sm-content">
            <div class="sm-title"><span class="sm-tag">Tool</span> JSON → Parse JSON</div>
            <div class="sm-desc">Take the text content from M2's response and parse it as JSON. This gives you clean variables like {{intent}}, {{confidence}}, {{hot_lead}}, and {{suggested_reply}} that you can map in the next modules.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="sm-row">
          <div class="sm-num">M4</div>
          <div class="sm-content">
            <div class="sm-title"><span class="sm-tag">Control</span> Router (4 Paths)</div>
            <div class="sm-desc">Add a Router module → create 4 paths: Path 1 = intent equals "buy" · Path 2 = intent equals "price" · Path 3 = intent equals "support" · Path 4 = intent equals "spam". Each path continues to its own modules below.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="sm-row">
          <div class="sm-num">M5</div>
          <div class="sm-content">
            <div class="sm-title"><span class="sm-tag">Action</span> HTTP → Send WhatsApp Reply (per path)</div>
            <div class="sm-desc">On each relevant path (buy / price / support), use the WhatsApp API to send the qualifying reply template back to the sender's number. Use the Phone Number ID and Access Token from Step 2. Spam path: no reply, skip to logging.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="sm-row">
          <div class="sm-num">M6</div>
          <div class="sm-content">
            <div class="sm-title"><span class="sm-tag">Action</span> Google Sheets → Add a Row</div>
            <div class="sm-desc">On ALL paths, append a row to your lead log sheet. Map: Timestamp → now() · Phone → sender number · Raw Message → original text · Intent → {{intent}} · Confidence → {{confidence}} · Summary → {{summary}} · Hot Lead → {{hot_lead}} · Status → "New".</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="sm-row">
          <div class="sm-num">M7</div>
          <div class="sm-content">
            <div class="sm-title"><span class="sm-tag">Filter</span> Alert — Buy Path Only</div>
            <div class="sm-desc">Add a Filter before this module: only continue if {{hot_lead}} equals true. Then add a Slack or Email module to send yourself an instant alert with the lead summary and the sender's phone number.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

